2.3.2 Selecting the threshold ğœ–
Now that you have estimated the Gaussian parameters, you can investigate which examples have a very high probability given this distribution and which examples have a very low probability.

The low probability examples are more likely to be the anomalies in our dataset.
One way to determine which examples are anomalies is to select a threshold based on a cross validation set.
In this section, you will complete the code in select_threshold to select the threshold ğœ€
 using the ğ¹1
 score on a cross validation set.

For this, we will use a cross validation set {(ğ‘¥(1)cv,ğ‘¦(1)cv),â€¦,(ğ‘¥(ğ‘šcv)cv,ğ‘¦(ğ‘šcv)cv)}
, where the label ğ‘¦=1
 corresponds to an anomalous example, and ğ‘¦=0
 corresponds to a normal example.
For each cross validation example, we will compute ğ‘(ğ‘¥(ğ‘–)cv)
. The vector of all of these probabilities ğ‘(ğ‘¥(1)cv),â€¦,ğ‘(ğ‘¥(ğ‘šcv)cv)
 is passed to select_threshold in the vector p_val.
The corresponding labels ğ‘¦(1)cv,â€¦,ğ‘¦(ğ‘šcv)cv
 are passed to the same function in the vector y_val.

